<dl id="n12069k"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12069k">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12069k"> 69(k)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ 8<sup>th</sup> wonder of world <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n12069k"><li>FW 71.14 </li><li><a href="../../flex/c/lexc.htm#n12069k">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/c/l39c.htm#n12069k">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n12069k">MS BL 47472-131</ms> </li><li>JJA 45:182 <a name="c3d" href="../../ff/fdra/cda.htm#c3d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/c/c3d.htm#n12069k">Draft: I.3&sect;1.3</a>/2.3/3.3</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Il est certain que la baie du Mont Saint-Michel, limit&eacute;e par le cap Lihou (Granville) et le Groin de Cancale, est plus bretonne que normande | par l&apos;&eacute;tendue de ses c&ocirc;tes, la nature de ses falaises et sa configuration g&eacute;n&eacute;rale; il ne lui manque que la profondeur de ses eaux pour &ecirc;tre tout &agrave; fait un <b>aber</b> armoricain. / Les Normands eux-m&ecirc;mes, si fiers de poss&eacute;der sur leur terre-marine &mdash; (ce mot est du trouv&egrave;re Wace) &mdash; <mark>la huiti&egrave;me merveille du monde</mark>, ont reconnu, de vieille date, que la baie appartient plus &agrave; la Bretagne qu&apos;&agrave; leur propre province. <br><font color="green">[It is certain that the bay of Mont Saint-Michel, between cape Lihou (Granville) and Groin de Cancale, is more Breton than Normand by the extent of its coast, the nature of its rockfaces and the general configuration; it only lacks water depth in order to be altogether an Armorican &lsquo;aber&rsquo;. The Normans themselves, so proud to have on their marine land (the expression was coined by the troubadour Wace) the <mark>eighth wonder of the world</mark>, have long realized that the bay belongs more to the Bretons than to their own province.]</font> <small> &Eacute;tienne Dupont, <a name="SMIN" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SMIN"><cite title="source">Le Mont Saint-Michel Inconnu</cite></a> (1912) 284-5</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
